  "Defaulting on a loan means failing to meet the repayment terms. Consequences include late fees, penalty interest rates, damage to credit score, and for secured loans, the lender may repossess the collateral (e.g., foreclosure on a home).": "",
  "What is the 'debt-to-income ratio' (DTI)?": "",
  "The ratio of your credit card balance to your credit limit": "",
  "The total amount of money you have saved divided by your annual income": "",
  "Your net worth divided by total liabilities": "",
  "Your total monthly debt payments divided by your gross monthly income, expressed as a percentage": "",
  "DTI measures what portion of your income goes toward debt payments. Lenders use it to assess whether you can afford additional debt. Most lenders prefer a DTI below 36%, and 43% is typically the maximum for qualified mortgages.": "",
  "What is an 'origination fee'?": "",
  "A monthly charge added to each loan payment": "",
  "The interest charged during the first month of the loan": "",
  "A one-time fee charged by the lender to process and underwrite a new loan, typically part of closing costs": "",
  "A penalty for late payments": "",
  "An origination fee is an upfront charge from the lender to cover the cost of processing the loan. It is usually expressed as a percentage of the loan amount (e.g., 0.5% to 1%) and is included in APR calculations.": "",
  "What is a 'prepayment penalty'?": "",
  "An extra charge for making payments on time": "",
  "The first payment due on a new loan": "",
  "A fee charged by the lender if you pay off the loan before the scheduled end date": "",
  "A reward for paying off a loan early": "",
  "Some lenders charge prepayment penalties to recoup lost interest income when borrowers pay off loans early. It is important to check for this provision before signing a loan agreement, as it can make refinancing or early payoff costly.": "",
  "What does 'collateral' mean in lending?": "",
  "An asset pledged by the borrower that the lender can seize if the borrower fails to repay the loan": "",
  "A type of insurance that covers loan payments": "",
  "Additional interest charged on a loan": "",
  "The co-signer's income verification documents": "",
  "Collateral is an asset that backs a secured loan. For a mortgage, the home is collateral; for an auto loan, the car is collateral. Collateral reduces the lender's risk, which is why secured loans typically have lower interest rates.": "",
  "What does 'loan term' mean?": "",
